{{Infobox language family |name=Angami–Pochuri |region=[[Nagaland]] |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Kuki-Chin–Naga languages|Kuki-Chin–Naga]]? |child1=[[Angami languages|Angami]] |child2=[[Pochuri languages|Pochuri]] |glotto=anga1286 |glottorefname=Angami–Pochuri }}
The '''Angami–Pochuri languages''' are a small family of [[Sino-Tibetan languages]] spoken in southern [[Nagaland]] and Northern Manipur of northeast [[India]]. Conventionally classified as "Naga", they are not clearly related to other [[Kuki-Chin–Naga languages|Naga languages]], and are conservatively classified as an independent branch of Sino-Tibetan, pending further research.
Coupe (2012)<ref>Coupe, Alexander R. 2012. Overcounting numeral systems and their relevance to sub-grouping in the Tibeto-Burman languages of Nagaland. Language and Linguistics / Academica Sinica 13. 193-220.</ref> considers the [[Ao languages]] to be most closely related to Angami–Pochuri as part of a wider ''Angami–Ao'' group.
==Languages== The '''Angami languages''' are: *[[Angami language|Angami]] *[[Chokri language|Chokri]] (Chakri, Chakhesang) *[[Kheza language|Kheza]] *[[Sopvoma language|Sopvoma]] (Mao) *[[Poula language|Poula]] (Poumai)
The '''Pochuri languages''' are: *[[Pochuri language|Pochuri]]–Meluri *[[Ntenyi language|Ntenyi]] (Northern Rengma) *[[Rengma language|Rengma]] *[[Sumi language|Sumi]] (Sema)
'''Rengma–Simi''' might form a third branch according to Burling (2003).<ref>Burling, R. (2003). The Tibeto-Burman languages of Northeastern India. In G. Thurgood & R. LaPolla (Eds.), The Sino-Tibetan Languages (pp. 169-191). London: Routledge.</ref><ref name="Glottolog" />
