{{Infobox language |name=Cuaiquer |nativename=''Awa Pit'' |states=[[Colombia]], [[Ecuador]] |ethnicity=15,000 [[Awa-Kwaiker people|Awa-Kwaiker]] (2007)<ref name=e18/> |speakers=13,000 |date=2008 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Barbacoan languages|Barbacoan]] |fam2=[[Awan languages|Awan]] |iso3=kwi |glotto=awac1239 |glottorefname=Awa-Cuaiquer }}
'''Awa''' or '''Awa pit''', also known as '''Cuaiquer''', is a [[Barbacoan]] language spoken by the [[Awa-Kwaiker people]], who inhabit territory straddling northern Ecuador and southern Colombia (the language is sometimes also referred to as '''Coaiquer''', '''Quaiquer''', or '''Kwaiker''' in Colombia, and as '''Awapit''' in Ecuador).<ref name="eth">[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=kwi Awa–Cuaiquer], per SIL, Ethnologue, 1986 and 1991. Retrieved 23 April 2012.</ref> Awa pit is classified by [[UNESCO]] as a severely endangered language.<ref>Haboud, Marleen; Adelaarurl, Willem (2008). [http://www.unesco.org/culture/languages-atlas/en/atlasmap/language-id-1261.html "Awapit" ]. In: Moseley, Christopher, ed (2010). ''Atlas of the World’s Languages in Danger'', 3rd edn, Paris. UNESCO Publishing (online version). Retrieved 23 April 2012.</ref>
==Speakers and characteristics== The Awa pit language has around 21 thousand speakers, mostly residing on the [[Colombia]]n Pacific slopes of the [[Andes]], with about a thousand in an adjacent area of [[Ecuador]].<ref name="eth"/> While most men also speak [[Spanish language|Spanish]], the women and children are predominantly monolingual.<ref name="eth"/> Literacy among Awa speakers is less than 1% in their native language and under 5% in the secondary Spanish language.<ref name="eth"/>
The Awa pit language has a subject–object–verb structure and has adopted the [[Latin script]].<ref name="eth"/> Grammatically, Awa pit uses a characteristic [[conjunct]]/[[Disjunct (linguistics)|disjunct]] system of verb suffixes for person-marking which displays similarities with some [[Tibeto-Burman languages]], such as the [[Nepal Bhasa|Newari]] language of Kathmandu.<ref>Curnow, Timothy Jowan (1997). [http://linguistlist.org/pubs/diss/browse-diss-action.cfm?DissID=560 A Grammar of Awa Pit (Cuaiquer): An indigenous language of south-western Colombia]. PhD Thesis, [[Australian National University]], Canberra. Retrieved 23 April 2012.</ref><ref name=Curnow2002>Curnow, Timothy Jowan (2 May 2002). [http://www.deepdyve.com/lp/de-gruyter/conjunct-disjunct-marking-in-awa-pit-YayWjdRuH5/1 "Conjunct/disjunct marking in Awa Pit"]. ''Linguistics&nbsp;–&nbsp;An Interdisciplinary Journal of the Language Sciences'' 40(3):611-627.{{subscription}}</ref><ref>Cysouw, Michael (2003). "The Paradigmatic Structure of Person Marking", p 43–44. Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|9780199554263}}</ref>
