{{Infobox language |name=Huishui Miao |nativename=''Mhong'' |altname= |states=[[China]] |region=[[Guizhou]] |ethnicity= |speakers=180,000 |date=1995 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Hmong-Mien |fam2=[[Hmongic languages|Hmongic]] |fam3=[[West Hmongic]] |fam4= |dia1=[[Raojia language|Raojia]] |lc1=hmc|ld1=Central |lc2=hme|ld2=Eastern |lc3=hmi|ld3=Northern |lc4=hmh|ld4=Southwestern |glotto=huis1239 |glottorefname=Huishui }}
'''Huishui Miao''', a.k.a. '''Huishui Hmong''', is a [[Miao languages|Miao language]] of China. It is named after [[Huishui County]], Guizhou, though not all varieties are spoken there. The endonym is ''Mhong'', though it shares this with [[Gejia language|Gejia]] and it is simply a variant spelling of [[Hmong language|Hmong]]. [[Raojia language|Raojia]] is closely related.
Huishui was given as a subgroup of [[Western Hmongic]] in Strecker (1987). Matisoff (2001) split it into four separate languages, and, conservatively, did not retain it as a group.
